{res}{txt}(running {bf:_gformula_bootstrap} on estimation sample)

Bootstrap replications ({res}50{txt})
{hline 4}{c +}{hline 3} 1 {hline 3}{c +}{hline 3} 2 {hline 3}{c +}{hline 3} 3 {hline 3}{c +}{hline 3} 4 {hline 3}{c +}{hline 3} 5 
..................................................    50
{res}{txt} 
G-computation formula estimates of the total causal effect and the natural direct/indirect effects

{col 5}Note: The total causal effect ({res}TCE{txt}) is a comparison between the
{col 11}mean potential outcome if, contrary to fact, all subjects were
{col 11}exposed, and the mean potential outcome if all subjects were
{col 11}unexposed. Writing X for the exposure, M for the mediator(s),
{col 11}and Y for the outcome and 0 for the baseline, then:

{res}{col 19}TCE{txt}=E[Y{X=1,M(X=1)}]-E[Y{X=0,M(X=0)}]

{col 11}The natural direct effect ({res}NDE{txt}) is a comparison between the
{col 11}mean of two potential outcomes. The first is the potential
{col 11}outcome if, contrary to fact, all subjects were exposed, and
{col 11}subjects' mediator(s) were set to their potential value(s)
{col 11}under no exposure. The second is the potential outcome if,
{col 11}contrary to fact, all subjects were unexposed. That is:

{res}{col 19}NDE{txt}=E[Y{X=1,M(X=0)}]-E[Y{X=0,M(X=0)}]

{col 11}The natural indirect effect ({res}NIE{txt}) is the difference between
{col 11}the {res}TCE{txt} and the {res}NDE{txt}. That is:

{res}{col 15}NIE{txt}={res}TCE{txt}-{res}NDE{txt}=E[Y{X=1,M(X=1)}]-E[Y{X=1,M(X=0)}]

{col 11}The proportion mediated ({res}PM{txt}) is the {res}NIE {txt}divided by
{col 11}the {res}TCE{txt}.

 
 
