{res}{txt} 
G-computation formula estimates of the total causal effect and the natural direct/indirect effects

{col 5}Note: The total causal effect ({res}TCE(k){txt}), comparing level k
{col 11}of the exposure against the baseline, is a comparison
{col 11}between the mean potential outcome if, contrary to fact,
{col 11}all subjects were exposed at level k, and the mean
{col 11}potential outcome if all subjects received the baseline
{col 11}level of exposure. Writing X for the exposure, M for the
{col 11}mediator(s), Y for the outcome, and 0 for the baseline:

{res}{col 19}TCE(k){txt}=E[Y{X=k,M(X=k)}]-E[Y{X=0,M(X=0)}]

{col 11}The natural direct effect ({res}NDE(k){txt}) is a comparison between the
{col 11}mean of two potential outcomes. The first is the potential
{col 11}outcome if, contrary to fact, all subjects received exposure
{col 11}k, and subjects' mediator(s) were set to their potential
{col 11}value(s) under baseline exposure. The second is the potential
{col 11}outcome if, contrary to fact, all subjects experienced the
{col 11}baseline exposure. That is:

{res}{col 19}NDE(k){txt}=E[Y{X=k,M(X=0)}]-E[Y{X=0,M(X=0)}]

{col 11}The natural indirect effect ({res}NIE(k){txt}) is the difference between
{col 11}the {res}TCE(k){txt} and the {res}NDE(k){txt}. That is:

{res}{col 15}NIE(k){txt}={res}TCE(k){txt}-{res}NDE(k){txt}=E[Y{X=k,M(X=k)}]-E[Y{X=k,M(X=0)}]

{col 11}The proportion mediated ({res}PM(k){txt}) is the {res}NIE(k) {txt}divided by
{col 11}the {res}TCE(k){txt}.

 
{col 10}Baseline value(s): 
{col 15}x={res}0
